Write a program that will ask the user to input a positive number; if it is not positive then print "not positive" and end execution.If this validation passes, then if the number is over 500 print "fractional"; otherwise print 500 divided by the number.  Either way print "done" as the last thing.

For this program, we will assume we get a number from the user and not a string like "go heels", so we will only be validating that the number is greater than 0.
Here is a pattern you can use for "if something is wrong in the input data, then end the program":
if ( boolean condition on input data ) { 
  alert("error message"); 
  return; // ends execution
}
We use the return statement to cause myMain to stop executing when the input data is bad. This validation code will go right after the prompt 
statement that gets the user input.
The remaining code -- after the validation -- looks a lot like a previous conditional program we wrote.

More about Functions 
We now revisit the abstraction called a function.  We have been writing and using a simple function ( myMain ) for a week or two now.  We have also been using functions that come with JavaScript (Math.sqrt, Math.floor, etc.) since nearly the beginning.  We will now learn more about how to write and use function like Math.sqrt() where we pass in some information and get a result back.  
We wrote one back in module on simple functions (it cubed its parameter and returned it).  Now we will practice more.
We will call the functions we write here simple utility functions.  They will be handy for asking (and answering) small but useful questions like "is this number an integer" or "is this number odd" in our programs as we progress.
We write a simple utility function in a way very similar to how we are writing myMain.  However, since we are passing information
in (like we do when we call Math.sqrt(4) for example) for the function to use while computing a result, we will have to specify a
parameter.  Also, since the point of a utility function is to get some result back, we will need to add a return 
statement to the body of the function when we define it.
To complete this problem, type in and execute this code:
"use strict";

function myMain ( ) {
   var x = 5;
   var dubx = double(x);
   alert(dubx);
}

function double ( num ) {
   var val = num*2;
   return val;
}

myMain();
Note that to do these programs with our own functions, we will need to write the myMain( ) function as we have been, and we will also write
another function (or several more).  These extra functions will be called by the code in the body of myMain.

Overview: Encapsulating validation 
We will now put our new knowledge of simple functions to work making input validation look cleaner in our programs.
The idea is that instead of asking 2 or 3 individual questions (like is this an integer? is this odd? etc.) in our main program
when the user gives input, we will put the questions together in the body of a new function named something like "validate".
We will pass the input from the user into the validate function as a parameter; the function will return a message indicating
what went wrong (or something like "ok" if all went right).
To complete this overview write the following program and run it:
"use strict";
function myMain() {
   var inp = prompt("input?");
   var result = validate(inp);
   alert(result);
}

function validate ( userInput ) {
   var retVal = userInput + ": OK" ;
   return retVal;
}

myMain();
Now this program is simply declaring all inputs to be OK, but it shows the basic structure we will need.

Basic Objects: Structured data 
Objects are collections of data with "tags" to identify the components.
You can think of an object as a container full of named data items.  The components of an object are called its "fields" or "properties".
Later we will see that objects can contain functions as well as data, but for now we will think of them as a wrapper around a
collection of named data items.  Although the data items in an object are called "fields" or "properties" we can also think of them
as variables.  They will behave like variables... we will be able to store data into them, and retrieve data from them, and use them in
expressions.
We will start with object literals.  An object literal is a way of specifying an object value directly, like a constant... like 5 is a number literal or
"go heels" is a string literal.
To complete this problem type in and run this code:
"use strict";

function myMain() {
   alert( {a:5, b:"hello"}.a );
   alert( {a:5, b:"hello"}.b );
}

myMain();
Here, the object literal (value) is  {a:5, b:"hello"} which contains two fields, tagged "a" and "b".  The "dot notation" is used to select a field.
Thus,  {a:5, b:"hello"}.a says to select the value of the field tagged "a" from the object, and the alert will print 5.
Now type in the following code:
"use strict";

function myMain() {
  var obj = {a:5, b:"hello"};
  alert( obj.a );
  alert( obj.b );
}

myMain();
If you run this (or submit it for score) you will see that it does the same thing as the first form.  In this second form, we create a variable and store the object
literal into it (same as doing "var x = 5;" with a number literal).  We now see that the dot notation, to select a field from an object, can be used after a variable name also.
This second form is by far the more heavily used way to create and access objects.
Even though we saw that objects do have literal values (like the {a:5, b:"hello"} ) there is a difference between a literal object and a literal number data value.  A number literal does not
have parts, or components; it is unstructured ... it has only one part.  In contrast, objects have parts -- they are constructed from components (the fields) and they are organized.
They are what we call structured data.  We will see that you can used an object as an abstract collection (by referring to the variable containing the object) or you can
use a piece of an object... you can access portions of the structure.  This is what the dot notation does.

Overview: Random numbers 
Random numbers are important mathematically for many problem solutions.  Statistical modeling depends on them to simulate the
unpredictable behavior seen in physical systems that we study by writing computer programs -- we call such programs "simulations".  Programming languages contain the capability to generate
random numbers when a program is executing.  In JavaScript, we use the function Math.random() to do this.
Math.random will generate and return a single random number between 0 and 1.  It might return 0, but it will never return 1.
Remember your interval notation from algebra? We write [0-1) for the range of the Math.random function, meaning it
produces a number x where 0 Math.random will return a different number every time it is called, but the value will always be in that range.  The numbers will be distributed uniformly (evenly) over that range, meaning the probability of getting any particular number with in the [0-1) range is the same as the probability or getting any other particular number.  
If you run a program that calls Math.random() many times, and graph the output with something like a bar chart, it will be flat (showing the uniformity)... it will NOT follow some other distribution shape such as a bell curve.
If you need a distribution other than uniform, you end up writing a program that uses Math.random but biases the output numbers as you need.
Type the following code into the Bricks editor window and execute it:
"use strict";

function myMain() {
  var ranNum = Math.random();
  alert(ranNum);
}

myMain();
Run this code several times locally to see how Math.random behaves.  Then submit it for score.

Arrays: Organizing data 
Arrays are structured data, meaning a way to organize a collection of data so that the components
may be systematically accessed.
It also is an abstraction, meaning we can deal with the entire data collection as a unit (as well as access
the individual elements in the collection).
We can think of an array as a numbered collection of storage slots.  The numbers begin with 0, and go upwards by 1.  An array has a name, like a simple
variable, and is declared like a variable.  But unlike a simple variable, to store or retrieve a data value we must specify the slot number (called the "index").
With an array, we must keep separate the difference between the slot number and the data value stored in that slot.  Slot numbers are always integer (type number);
the data stored in the array slot itself can be any type (including an object, or even another array as we will see).
Here is an array of cars over at the Carolina Inn.  In slot 2 is a silver Volvo.  In slot 3 is a white Cadillac.  It's not difficult with physical cars to see the difference 
between the integer 2 (slot number) and a Volvo ("data" stored in the slot). There will be a bit more confusion when we want to store number data in array slots that
are numbered. .
We can also think of an array as a row of mail boxes.  Each box has a number (address), and contents (the mail). We will have syntax in JavaScript to
specify the address, and different syntax to open the box at an address and put in (take out) the mail.  To open and use a mailbox (array slot) we
put square brackets after the array variable name (like " arr[ ... ] " ).  To specify an address (slot number) we put an expression that evaluates to an integer
inside the square brackets (like " arr[ 5 ] " or " arr[ x+3 ] " ).
Type in and execute this code (it is global code, that's ok here):
"use strict";

function myMain() {
   var data = [ 7, "smith", -4.25, true ];
   alert(data.length);  
   alert(data[0]);
   alert(data[1]);
   alert(data[2]);
   alert(data[3]);
   alert(data[10-7]);
   alert( data[10 - data[0] ] ) ;
   alert(data[0] * data[2]);
   alert(data[Math.sqrt(4)]);
   var x = 2;
   alert(data[x]);
   var arr = data;  // copies the entire array as a whole
   alert(arr[0]);
}

myMain();
To know how many items are in an array, use the "length" property.  For the variable "data" above the 
expression "data.length" tells how many items are stored in that array (in this case, 4 elements).
To access an array element we use an expression inside "[" "]" square brackets.
The expression must evaluate to a non-negative integer.
In this example we use mostly integer literals; in future programs we will use variable names, as well
as more complex expressions like 2*x +1, etc.
Also, arrays subscripts (slots numbers) always begin with 0.  
This creates a bit of confusion until you are used to it, since
the first element in the array is at slot 0.  An array with 2 items in it will use subscripts 0 and 1.  Just
pay attention when you write code and think carefully about the expressions you use for subscripts.
In the example above, we see that arr has 4 elements and uses slot numbers 0 through 3.

