Searching: A big problem 
Sorting and Searching are two large important categories of problems in Computing Science.
You use them all the time in the software you use daily.  Go to eBay, for example, and try to find and buy something you have in mind.
You first search for it (find all blue UNC coffee mugs) and then the sort the output (put them in order of lowest price to highest).
Sorting is for later (and perhaps a later class).  
Searching is first.  Searching is the process of examining the data elements in a collection (arrays here) to see which elements match some criterion, or meet some requirement we have
for the needs of some computation. "Find all elements in an array that are prime numbers", or "Find the first element in an array that is negative", or "check the elements in this
array to see if they are all in alphabetic order", or "does this array of names contain someone named "Jane Doe".  These are examples of searches.  
We will be learning in this module how to systematically
go through an array, looking at every element slot-by-slot and comparing them to each other or to some value we are trying to match.
Most of the searching we do in arrays will use for-loops.  This is because the array lengths are known and are convenient as loop control parameters.
Type in the following code to search in an array:
"use strict";

function myMain() {
  var arr = [3,11,438,-21,895,67,1101,19,4.3,-6];
  for (var i=0; i &lt; arr.length; i++) {
    if ((arr[i]%3)===0) { 
      alert(arr[i] + ": multiple of 3"); 
    }
  }
}

myMain();
Here, the for loop allows us to examine the array slots in order, starting at 0 and going to the last slot in use.  Each time we do the loop body
we examine the slot number that the loop index variable "i" contains as value.  We are looking for multiples of 3, and if we find an array 
element that is one, we print out that value.

Functions are first-class values 
Functions in JavaScript are what we call "first class values".  This means a function is a "value" of some type (type "function") just as
5 is a value of type number.  First class values can be assigned to variables.We are already familiar with this using number (or string) data. Consider this code:
  var x = 8;
  var y;
  y = x;
  alert(x);
  alert(y);
We exect that 8 will get printed by each alert statement.  By assigning 8 to x, and then by assigning the contents of x to y, we expect that the variable "y" is, in essence,
a name for the value 8 just as "x" is a name for the value 8.  The value 8 is the same, no matter which name (variable) we use to denote the value.  Either way, using either variable,
we get the number value 8, the same value that we get when we double the number value 4.  There is only one number value 8, but we may denote it many different ways.
Now consider this code:
"use strict";

function myMain ( ) {
   alert( double(5) );
}

function double ( n ) {  return 2*n; }

myMain();
In this program we define a function "double" that takes one argument.  When called, function "double" multiplies its argument by 2 and returns that value.
We have defined using the "function" keyword that we are accustomed to using for function definitions.  Function "myMain" calls "double" on the number value 4 and 
alerts the returned result.
Now let's add some code to myMain:
"use strict";

function myMain ( ) {
  var dubble;
  dubble = double; // assigns the function value bound to "double" to the name "dubble"
  alert( double(5) );  // note by color that "double" is a global name
  alert( dubble(5) );  // note by color that "dubble" is a local name inside myMain
}

function double ( n ) {  return 2*n; }

myMain();
This shows one function (the code that multiplies its argument by 2) with two different names ("double", and "dubble").
We can make that function code execute by calling it with the "double" name, or with the "dubble" name; we do both in this program.
This is the same thing we did before with a number value, except we have now done it with a function value.  The function value
is the code that constitutes the definition, and that is executed when the function runs.  We say that the names "double" and
"dubble" are bound to the function value.  One way to bind a name to a function value is with the "function keyword".
Now we see that another way is to take the function value that one name denotes and bind it to another name via assignment.
Since the function "double" is declared at the global level, the name "double" is visible inside myMain, and can be used inside myMain.
If "double" were not visible inside myMain we could not call the function.  Since it is visible, we can not only call it to make
it execute, but we can assign it to some other variable.  Then we have two "names" for the one function value (the function that
multiplies its single argument by 2 and returns that value).  The function value is not the name -- it is the code.
