Recursion: Functions that call themselves 
Recursion is a very useful programming technique in which a function calls itself (re-cursion means re-occurring) in order to get a solution to a smaller or simpler
version of the problem that it is trying to solve.
For some problems, recursive code is simpler than equivalent code that is non-recursive -- easier to write, and more compact and less complex.
But the concept can be confusing, especially when first learning programming.  We will just get a taste of it in this module without going into in in deep detail.
The key to recursion is to make sure when the function calls itself, the problem that is passed to that call is a smaller or simpler version.
We think of a recursive function as saying "well now, if I let some function solve a smaller or simpler version of my problem, then  I know how
to use that smaller solution to solve my bigger problem."
Every recursive function will have two main parts:
the base casethe recursive callWe will write the base case first, and the base case will not recurse (will not call the function again). The base case is the simplest verion of the problem,
where the result is known and can be returned directly. The base case will usually be a test to see if the parameter is some smallest value.
The base case is very important. Leaving it out can make your recursive function run forever when it is called.
The base case is the trigger that ends the sequence of function calls that is a recursion.
If the base case does not apply, then we enter the recursive case, where the function calls itself, captures the return value, and then uses that simpler
return value to construct a solution it can return for it's own execution.
Examples will make all this much easier to visualize.
Put this code in your editor window and run it:
"use strict";

function myMain ( ) {
  var N = 5;
  alert("iteration ...");
  sequenceIter( N );
}

function sequenceIter ( n ) {
  for (var i=n; i>=0; i--) {
    alert(i);
  }
}

myMain();
When you run this locally you will see it generates a sequence of numbers as output: 5,4,3,2,1,0.  Do not submit it for score yet.
Now put this code in your editor window and execute it:
"use strict";

function myMain ( ) {
  var N = 5;
  alert("iteration ...");
  sequenceIter( N );
  alert("recursion ...");
  sequenceRecur( N );
}

function sequenceRecur( n ) {
  alert(n);
  if (n===0) { return; }     // base case
  sequenceRecur(n-1);   // recursive case
}

function sequenceIter ( n ) {
  for (var i=n; i>=0; i--) {
    alert(i);
  }
}

myMain();
This code now generated the sequence with both iteration, and with a recursive function ("sequenceRecur").  You see both functions do the same thing... one using looping
and no further function calls, and one using recursion.

Parsing: Decomposing text strings 
In this module we will learn a little about "parsing", which is breaking up text strings into pieces... into a collection of smaller strings, or components.
Parsing is part of many computing applications.  For example, in order to execute your JavaScript program, a compiler or interpreter must take the 
single text string that is your program and find all the important substring pieces... components like the keywords "function" and "true" and "while"... 
variable names, and number constants... all parts within the one long program string.  
We will see how to do a simple form of this using some JavaScript built-in string functions.
The string type in JavaScript has some built-in methods (functions) that you can ask any string to execute.  
The one we will use to parse is the "split" function.  You should google "JavaScript string split" and read the
details.  It takes a parameter, which is a single character; and it returns an array of strings.  The split functions will break the string that executes it into parts using 
the character that is sent as parameter to define the boundaries between parts; the parts will be placed into successive locations in the array that is returned.
For example, consider this code:
var long = "alpha beta gamma";
var parts= long.split(" ");
The second line causes the string "long" to be divided into 3 substrings using the blank as the separator.  This means the array "parts" has "alpha" in parts[0], "beta" in parts[1].
and "gamma" stored in parts[2].  Try this code, and alert elements from the array "parts" to see how split works.
The split function can divide a string using any character as the break point, not just a blank. For example, if you want to get a string of data (from a database, perhaps) and it
consists of several numbers separates by commas, you can break the data string down this way:
var data = "123,24.571,15,-37.2,0.01" ;
var nums = data.split(",");
alert(nums[0]);
alert(nums[3]);
If you try this code, you will see the numbers "123" and "-37" printed out in separate alert boxes.
Note that the elements in the array "nums" are still strings (that look like numbers). If you need real numeric data you still need to convert
the string data to number data (with the Number() function).
To see this, run the code above and add these lines at the end:
alert(nums[0]+nums[1]);  // string concatenation
alert(Number(nums[0]) + Number(nums[1]));  // numerical arithmetic
To complete this overview, type in the following program, execute it, then submit it for score.
"use strict";

function myMain() {
  var text = "see how parsing breaks up strings";
  var arr = text.split(" ");
  alert(arr[2]);
  alert(arr[3]);
  alert(arr[arr.length-1]);
}

myMain();

